<li id="cite_note-D.26L-19"><b><a href="#cite_ref-D.26L_19-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFTamara_M._Davis.2C_Charles_H._Lineweaver2000">Tamara M. Davis, Charles H. Lineweaver (2000). "<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0011070v2" class="external text" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0011070v2" rel="nofollow">Superluminal Recessional Velocities</a>". <i>ArXiv preprint</i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0011070v2" class="external free" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0011070v2" rel="nofollow">http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0011070v2</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Superluminal+Recessional+Velocities&amp;rft.jtitle=ArXiv+preprint&amp;rft.aulast=Tamara+M.+Davis%2C+Charles+H.+Lineweaver&amp;rft.au=Tamara+M.+Davis%2C+Charles+H.+Lineweaver&amp;rft.date=2000&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farxiv.org%2Fabs%2Fastro-ph%2F0011070v2&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Redshift"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Harrison1-20">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Harrison1_20-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Harrison1_20-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> The distinction is made clear in <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFEdward_Robert_Harrison2000">Edward Robert Harrison (2000). <i><a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=-8PJbcA2lLoC&amp;pg=PA315#PPA306,M1" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=-8PJbcA2lLoC&amp;pg=PA315#PPA306,M1" rel="nofollow">Cosmology: The Science of the Universe</a></i> (2 ed.). Cambridge University Press. pp.&#160;306<i>ff</i>. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/052166148X" class="internal">ISBN 052166148X</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=-8PJbcA2lLoC&amp;pg=PA315#PPA306,M1" class="external free" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=-8PJbcA2lLoC&amp;pg=PA315#PPA306,M1" rel="nofollow">http://books.google.com/books?id=-8PJbcA2lLoC&amp;pg=PA315#PPA306,M1</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Cosmology%3A+The+Science+of+the+Universe&amp;rft.aulast=Edward+Robert+Harrison&amp;rft.au=Edward+Robert+Harrison&amp;rft.date=2000&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3B306%27%27ff%27%27&amp;rft.edition=2&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rft.isbn=052166148X&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D-8PJbcA2lLoC%26pg%3DPA315%23PPA306%2CM1&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Redshift"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-21"><b><a href="#cite_ref-21" title="">^</a></b> This is only true in a universe where there are no <a href="/wiki/Peculiar_velocity" title="Peculiar velocity">peculiar velocities</a>. Otherwise, redshifts combine as
<dl>
<dd><span class="texhtml">1 + <i>z</i> = (1 + <i>z</i><sub>Doppler</sub>)(1 + <i>z</i><sub>expansion</sub>)</span></dd>
</dl>
which yields solutions where certain objects that "recede" are blue shifted and other objects that "approach" are redshifted. For more on this bizarre result see Davis, T. M., Lineweaver, C. H., and Webb, J. K. "<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0104349/" class="external text" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0104349/" rel="nofollow">Solutions to the tethered galaxy problem in an expanding universe and the observation of receding blue shifted objects</a>", <i><a href="/wiki/American_Journal_of_Physics" title="American Journal of Physics">American Journal of Physics</a></i> (2003), <b>71</b> 358–364.</li>
<li id="cite_note-Peebles-1993-22">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Peebles-1993_22-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Peebles-1993_22-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Peebles-1993_22-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> Peebles (1993).</li>
<li id="cite_note-23"><b><a href="#cite_ref-23" title="">^</a></b> Measurements of the peculiar velocities out to 5 <a href="/wiki/Parsec" title="Parsec">Mpc</a> using the <a href="/wiki/Hubble_Space_Telescope" title="Hubble Space Telescope">Hubble Space Telescope</a> were reported in 2003 by Karachentsev et al. <i>Local galaxy flows within 5 Mpc</i>. 02/2003 <i><a href="/wiki/Astronomy_and_Astrophysics" title="Astronomy and Astrophysics">Astronomy and Astrophysics</a></i>, <b>398</b>, 479-491.<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0211011" class="external autonumber" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0211011" rel="nofollow">[4]</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-Kuhn-24"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Kuhn_24-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFTheo_Koupelis.2C_Karl_F._Kuhn2007">Theo Koupelis, Karl F. Kuhn (2007). <i><a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=6rTttN4ZdyoC&amp;pg=PA556#PPA557,M1" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=6rTttN4ZdyoC&amp;pg=PA556#PPA557,M1" rel="nofollow">In Quest of the Universe</a></i> (5 ed.). Jones &amp; Bartlett Publishers. p.&#160;557. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0763743879" class="internal">ISBN 0763743879</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=6rTttN4ZdyoC&amp;pg=PA556#PPA557,M1" class="external free" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=6rTttN4ZdyoC&amp;pg=PA556#PPA557,M1" rel="nofollow">http://books.google.com/books?id=6rTttN4ZdyoC&amp;pg=PA556#PPA557,M1</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=In+Quest+of+the+Universe&amp;rft.aulast=Theo+Koupelis%2C+Karl+F.+Kuhn&amp;rft.au=Theo+Koupelis%2C+Karl+F.+Kuhn&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B557&amp;rft.edition=5&amp;rft.pub=Jones+%26+Bartlett+Publishers&amp;rft.isbn=0763743879&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D6rTttN4ZdyoC%26pg%3DPA556%23PPA557%2CM1&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Redshift"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Lewis-25"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Lewis_25-0" title="">^</a></b> "It is perfectly valid to interpret the equations of relativity in terms of an expanding space. The mistake is to push analogies too far and imbue space with physical properties that are not consistent with the equations of relativity." <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFGeraint_F._Lewis_.27.27et_al..27.272008">Geraint F. Lewis <i>et al.</i> (2008). "<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/0805.2197v1" class="external text" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/0805.2197v1" rel="nofollow">Cosmological Radar Ranging in an Expanding Universe</a>". <i>Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society</i>: 960-964<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/0805.2197v1" class="external free" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/0805.2197v1" rel="nofollow">http://arxiv.org/abs/0805.2197v1</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Cosmological+Radar+Ranging+in+an+Expanding+Universe&amp;rft.jtitle=Monthly+Notices+of+the+Royal+Astronomical+Society&amp;rft.aulast=Geraint+F.+Lewis+%27%27et+al.%27%27&amp;rft.au=Geraint+F.+Lewis+%27%27et+al.%27%27&amp;rft.date=2008&amp;rft.pages=960-964&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farxiv.org%2Fabs%2F0805.2197v1&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Redshift"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Chodorowski-26"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Chodorowski_26-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFMichal_Chodorowski2007">Michal Chodorowski (2007). "<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0601171v2" class="external text" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0601171v2" rel="nofollow">Is space really expanding? A counterexample</a>". <i>Concepts Phys</i> <b>4</b>: 17-34<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0601171v2" class="external free" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0601171v2" rel="nofollow">http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0601171v2</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Is+space+really+expanding%3F+A+counterexample&amp;rft.jtitle=Concepts+Phys&amp;rft.aulast=Michal+Chodorowski&amp;rft.au=Michal+Chodorowski&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.volume=4&amp;rft.pages=17-34&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farxiv.org%2Fabs%2Fastro-ph%2F0601171v2&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Redshift"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
