<li id="cite_note-Weinberg_Cosmology-32"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Weinberg_Cosmology_32-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFSteven_Weinberg2008">Steven Weinberg (2008). <i><a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=48C-ym2EmZkC&amp;pg=PA11" class="external text" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=48C-ym2EmZkC&amp;pg=PA11" rel="nofollow">Cosmology</a></i>. Oxford University Press. p.&#160;11. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780198526827" class="internal">ISBN 9780198526827</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=48C-ym2EmZkC&amp;pg=PA11" class="external free" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=48C-ym2EmZkC&amp;pg=PA11" rel="nofollow">http://books.google.com/books?id=48C-ym2EmZkC&amp;pg=PA11</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Cosmology&amp;rft.aulast=Steven+Weinberg&amp;rft.au=Steven+Weinberg&amp;rft.date=2008&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B11&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.isbn=9780198526827&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D48C-ym2EmZkC%26pg%3DPA11&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Redshift"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-33"><b><a href="#cite_ref-33" title="">^</a></b> Odenwald &amp; Fienberg 1993</li>
<li id="cite_note-34"><b><a href="#cite_ref-34" title="">^</a></b> Speed faster than light is allowed because the <a href="/wiki/Metric_expansion_of_space" title="Metric expansion of space">expansion</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Spacetime" title="Spacetime">spacetime</a> <a href="/wiki/Metric_(mathematics)" title="Metric (mathematics)">metric</a> is described by <a href="/wiki/General_relativity" title="General relativity">general relativity</a> in terms of sequences of only locally valid inertial frames as opposed to a global <a href="/wiki/Minkowski_metric" title="Minkowski metric" class="mw-redirect">Minkowski metric</a>. Expansion faster than light is an integrated effect over many local inertial frames and is allowed because no single inertial frame is involved. The speed-of-light limitation applies only locally. See <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFMichal_Chodorowski2007">Michal Chodorowski (2007). "<a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0601171v2" class="external text" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0601171v2" rel="nofollow">Is space really expanding? A counterexample</a>". <i>Concepts Phys</i> <b>4</b>: 17-34<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0601171v2" class="external free" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0601171v2" rel="nofollow">http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0601171v2</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Is+space+really+expanding%3F+A+counterexample&amp;rft.jtitle=Concepts+Phys&amp;rft.aulast=Michal+Chodorowski&amp;rft.au=Michal+Chodorowski&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.volume=4&amp;rft.pages=17-34&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farxiv.org%2Fabs%2Fastro-ph%2F0601171v2&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Redshift"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-35"><b><a href="#cite_ref-35" title="">^</a></b> M. Weiss, What Causes the Hubble Redshift?, entry in the Physics <a href="/wiki/FAQ" title="FAQ">FAQ</a> (1994), available via <a href="/wiki/John_Baez" title="John Baez" class="mw-redirect">John Baez</a>'s <a href="http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/physics/Relativity/GR/hubble.html" class="external text" title="http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/physics/Relativity/GR/hubble.html" rel="nofollow">website</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-36"><b><a href="#cite_ref-36" title="">^</a></b> See for example, Chant, C. A., "<a href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=1930JRASC..24..390C&amp;db_key=AST&amp;data_type=HTML&amp;format=&amp;high=42ca922c9c27309" class="external text" title="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=1930JRASC..24..390C&amp;db_key=AST&amp;data_type=HTML&amp;format=&amp;high=42ca922c9c27309" rel="nofollow">Notes and Queries (Telescopes and Observatory Equipment-The Einstein Shift of Solar Lines)</a>" (1930) <i>Journal of the Royal Astronomical Society of Canada</i>, Vol. 24, p.390</li>
<li id="cite_note-37"><b><a href="#cite_ref-37" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFEinstein1907"><a href="/wiki/Albert_Einstein" title="Albert Einstein">Einstein, A</a> (1907). "Unknown title". <i>Jahrbuch der Radioaktivität und Elektronik</i> <b>4</b>: 411–?.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Unknown+title&amp;rft.jtitle=Jahrbuch+der+Radioaktivit%C3%A4t+und+Elektronik&amp;rft.aulast=Einstein&amp;rft.aufirst=A&amp;rft.au=Einstein%2C+A&amp;rft.date=1907&amp;rft.volume=4&amp;rft.pages=411%26ndash%3B%3F&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Redshift"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-38"><b><a href="#cite_ref-38" title="">^</a></b> R. V. Pound and G. A. Rebka Jr., Apparent weight of photons, <i>Phys. Rev. Lett.</i> <b>4</b>, 337 (1960). <a href="http://prola.aps.org/abstract/PRL/v4/i7/p337_1" class="external autonumber" title="http://prola.aps.org/abstract/PRL/v4/i7/p337_1" rel="nofollow">[5]</a> This paper was the first measurement.</li>
<li id="cite_note-39"><b><a href="#cite_ref-39" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFSachs.5B.5BArthur_Michael_Wolfe.7CWolfe.2C_A._M..5D.5D1967"><a href="/wiki/Rainer_Kurt_Sachs" title="Rainer Kurt Sachs">Sachs, R. K.</a>; <a href="/wiki/Arthur_Michael_Wolfe" title="Arthur Michael Wolfe">Wolfe, A. M.</a> (1967). "<i>Perturbations of a cosmological model and angular variations of the cosmic microwave background</i>". <i>Astrophysical Journal</i> <b>147</b> (73): 73. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<span class="neverexpand"><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1086%2F148982" class="external text" title="http://dx.doi.org/10.1086%2F148982" rel="nofollow">10.1086/148982</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=%27%27Perturbations+of+a+cosmological+model+and+angular+variations+of+the+cosmic+microwave+background%27%27&amp;rft.jtitle=Astrophysical+Journal&amp;rft.aulast=Sachs&amp;rft.aufirst=R.+K.&amp;rft.au=Sachs%2C+R.+K.&amp;rft.au=%5B%5BArthur+Michael+Wolfe%7CWolfe%2C+A.+M.%5D%5D&amp;rft.date=1967&amp;rft.volume=147&amp;rft.issue=73&amp;rft.pages=73&amp;rft_id=info:doi/10.1086%2F148982&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Redshift"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-reboul-40"><b><a href="#cite_ref-reboul_40-0" title="">^</a></b> When cosmological redshifts were first discovered, <a href="/wiki/Fritz_Zwicky" title="Fritz Zwicky">Fritz Zwicky</a> proposed an effect known as <a href="/wiki/Tired_light" title="Tired light">tired light</a>. While usually considered for historical interests, it is sometimes, along with <a href="/wiki/Intrinsic_redshift" title="Intrinsic redshift">intrinsic redshift</a> suggestions, utilized by <a href="/wiki/Nonstandard_cosmologies" title="Nonstandard cosmologies" class="mw-redirect">nonstandard cosmologies</a>. In 1981, H. J. Reboul summarised many <a href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=1981A%26AS...45..129R&amp;db_key=AST&amp;data_type=HTML&amp;format=&amp;high=42ca922c9c23806" class="external text" title="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=1981A%26AS...45..129R&amp;db_key=AST&amp;data_type=HTML&amp;format=&amp;high=42ca922c9c23806" rel="nofollow">alternative redshift mechanisms</a> that had been discussed in the literature since the 1930s. In 2001, <a href="/wiki/Geoffrey_Burbidge" title="Geoffrey Burbidge">Geoffrey Burbidge</a> remarked in a <a href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=2001PASP..113..899B&amp;db_key=AST&amp;data_type=HTML" class="external text" title="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=2001PASP..113..899B&amp;db_key=AST&amp;data_type=HTML" rel="nofollow">review</a> that the wider astronomical community has marginalized such discussions since the 1960s. Burbidge and <a href="/wiki/Halton_Arp" title="Halton Arp">Halton Arp</a>, while investigating the mystery of <a href="/wiki/Quasar#History_of_quasar_observation" title="Quasar">the nature of quasars</a>, tried to develop alternative redshift mechanisms, and very few of their fellow scientists acknowledged let alone accepted their work. Moreover, Goldhaber <i>et al</i>. 2001; "Timescale Stretch Parameterization of Type Ia Supernova B-Band Lightcurves", ApJ, 558:359-386, 2001 September 1 pointed out that alternative theories are unable to account for timescale stretch observed in <a href="/wiki/Type_Ia_supernovae" title="Type Ia supernovae" class="mw-redirect">type Ia supernovae</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-41"><b><a href="#cite_ref-41" title="">^</a></b> For a review of the subject of photometry, consider Budding, E., <i>Introduction to Astronomical Photometry</i>, Cambridge University Press (September 24, 1993), <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0521418674" class="internal">ISBN 0-521-41867-4</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-42"><b><a href="#cite_ref-42" title="">^</a></b> The technique was first described by Baum, W. A.: 1962, in G. C. McVittie (ed.), <i>Problems of extra-galactic research</i>, p. 390, IAU Symposium No. 15</li>
<li id="cite_note-43"><b><a href="#cite_ref-43" title="">^</a></b> Bolzonella, M.; Miralles, J.-M.; Pelló, R., <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0003380" class="external text" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0003380" rel="nofollow">Photometric redshifts based on standard SED fitting procedures</a>, <i><a href="/wiki/Astronomy_and_Astrophysics" title="Astronomy and Astrophysics">Astronomy and Astrophysics</a></i>, <b>363</b>, p.476–492 (2000).</li>
<li id="cite_note-44"><b><a href="#cite_ref-44" title="">^</a></b> A pedagogical overview of the K-correction by David Hogg and other members of the <a href="/wiki/Sloan_Digital_Sky_Survey" title="Sloan Digital Sky Survey">SDSS</a> collaboration can be found at <a href="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0210394" class="external text" title="http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0210394" rel="nofollow">astro-ph</a>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-45"><b><a href="#cite_ref-45" title="">^</a></b> The <a href="/w/index.php?title=Exoplanet_Tracker&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Exoplanet Tracker (page does not exist)">Exoplanet Tracker</a> is the newest observing project to use this technique, able to track the redshift variations in multiple objects at once, as reported in Ge, Jian et al. <a href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-data_query?bibcode=2006ApJ...648..683G&amp;link_type=ARTICLE&amp;db_key=AST" class="external text" title="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-data_query?bibcode=2006ApJ...648..683G&amp;link_type=ARTICLE&amp;db_key=AST" rel="nofollow">The First Extrasolar Planet Discovered with a New-Generation High-Throughput Doppler Instrument</a>, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Astrophysical_Journal" title="The Astrophysical Journal" class="mw-redirect">The Astrophysical Journal</a></i>, 2006 <b>648</b>, Issue 1, pp. 683-695.<a href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=2006ApJ...648..683G&amp;db_key=AST&amp;data_type=HTML&amp;format=&amp;high=445165d66216614" class="external autonumber" title="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=2006ApJ...648..683G&amp;db_key=AST&amp;data_type=HTML&amp;format=&amp;high=445165d66216614" rel="nofollow">[6]</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-46"><b><a href="#cite_ref-46" title="">^</a></b> Libbrecht, Ken G., <a href="http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-iarticle_query?1988SSRv...47..275L&amp;data_type=PDF_HIGH&amp;type=PRINTER&amp;filetype=.pdf" class="external text" title="http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-iarticle_query?1988SSRv...47..275L&amp;data_type=PDF_HIGH&amp;type=PRINTER&amp;filetype=.pdf" rel="nofollow">Solar and stellar seismology</a>, <i>Space Science Reviews</i>, 1988 <b>37</b> n. 3–4, 275–301.</li>
<li id="cite_note-47"><b><a href="#cite_ref-47" title="">^</a></b> In 1871 <a href="/wiki/Hermann_Carl_Vogel" title="Hermann Carl Vogel">Hermann Carl Vogel</a> measured the rotation rate of <a href="/wiki/Venus" title="Venus">Venus</a>. <a href="/wiki/Vesto_Slipher" title="Vesto Slipher">Vesto Slipher</a> was working on such measurements when he turned his attention to spiral nebulae.</li>
<li id="cite_note-48"><b><a href="#cite_ref-48" title="">^</a></b> An early review by <a href="/wiki/Jan_Hendrick_Oort" title="Jan Hendrick Oort" class="mw-redirect">Oort, J. H.</a> on the subject: <a href="http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-iarticle_query?1970A%26A.....7..381O&amp;data_type=PDF_HIGH&amp;type=PRINTER&amp;filetype=.pdf" class="external text" title="http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-iarticle_query?1970A%26A.....7..381O&amp;data_type=PDF_HIGH&amp;type=PRINTER&amp;filetype=.pdf" rel="nofollow">The formation of galaxies and the origin of the high-velocity hydrogen</a>, <a href="/wiki/Astronomy_and_Astrophysics" title="Astronomy and Astrophysics">Astronomy and Astrophysics</a>, <b>7</b>, 381 (1970) <a href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=1970A%26A.....7..381O&amp;db_key=AST&amp;data_type=HTML&amp;format=&amp;high=4504216b9b04182" class="external autonumber" title="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=1970A%26A.....7..381O&amp;db_key=AST&amp;data_type=HTML&amp;format=&amp;high=4504216b9b04182" rel="nofollow">[7]</a>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-49"><b><a href="#cite_ref-49" title="">^</a></b> Asaoka, Ikuko, <a href="http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-iarticle_query?1989PASJ...41..763A&amp;data_type=PDF_HIGH&amp;type=PRINTER&amp;filetype=.pdf" class="external text" title="http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-iarticle_query?1989PASJ...41..763A&amp;data_type=PDF_HIGH&amp;type=PRINTER&amp;filetype=.pdf" rel="nofollow">X-ray spectra at infinity from a relativistic accretion disk around a Kerr black hole</a>, <i>Astronomical Society of Japan, Publications</i> (ISSN 0004-6264), <i>41</i> no. 4, 1989, p. 763–778 <a href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/bib_query?1989PASJ...41..763A" class="external autonumber" title="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/bib_query?1989PASJ...41..763A" rel="nofollow">[8]</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-50"><b><a href="#cite_ref-50" title="">^</a></b> Rybicki, G. B. and A. R. Lightman, <i>Radiative Processes in Astrophysics</i>, John Wiley &amp; Sons, 1979, p. 288 <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0471827592" class="internal">ISBN 0-471-82759-2</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-51"><b><a href="#cite_ref-51" title="">^</a></b> An accurate measurement of the cosmic microwave background was achieved by the <a href="/wiki/COBE" title="COBE" class="mw-redirect">COBE</a> experiment. The final published temperature of 2.73 K was reported in this paper: Fixsen, D. J.; Cheng, E. S.; Cottingham, D. A.; Eplee, R. E., Jr.; Isaacman, R. B.; Mather, J. C.; Meyer, S. S.; Noerdlinger, P. D.; Shafer, R. A.; Weiss, R.; Wright, E. L.; Bennett, C. L.; Boggess, N. W.; Kelsall, T.; Moseley, S. H.; Silverberg, R. F.; Smoot, G. F.; Wilkinson, D. T.. (1994). "Cosmic microwave background dipole spectrum measured by the COBE FIRAS instrument", <i>Astrophysical Journal</i>, 420, 445. The most accurate measurement as of 2006 was achieved by the <a href="/wiki/Wilkinson_Microwave_Anisotropy_Probe" title="Wilkinson Microwave Anisotropy Probe">WMAP</a> experiment.</li>
